defaultMAIN TOPICSdefault&#xa0;default2.1.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe safety question – a paradoxdefault:default We believe there is an apparent, but not actual, contradiction at work here. 
default2.2.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOn the one hand, cyclists are at risk from a wide variety of law- and rule-breaking behaviour by motorised road users. Much of this has been exacerbated by accommodating these b
defaultehaviours in traditional forms of highway design and also motor vehicle design. This kind of danger should be seen as simply intolerable and unacceptable. This should be based not just on the fact that people are dissuaded from cycling by danger – although
default this does occur - but because it is simply wrong: the behaviours concerned are often illegal and frequently endanger other road users as well.
default2.3.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultOn the other hand, it is important to stress that cyclists in the UK, and particularly in urban areas
default, have
default very
default low chances of being seriously injured, and even lower ones of being killed. Overemphasising the chances of being hurt distorts the picture of cycling, not least in inhibiting people who wish to cycle from doing so – denying them health benefits due to fe
defaultar of danger. A feature of an anti-cycling culture is the persistent tendency to see cycling as “the problem”. Part of this is the “dangerising” of cycling, seeing it as an activity which is inherently hazardous, particularly if there are any motor vehicle
defaults anywhere nearby.
default2.4.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default It is absolutely central to any successful strategy that this state of affairs is seen as the paradox it is. Cycling, particularly in the areas where there is a lot of cycling already, should be seen as the low-risk activity it is. This
default should not, however, detract from promoting a step change in reducing danger to cyclists from motor vehicular traffic, by whatever means – law enforcement and sentencing, training, highway and infrastructure engineering – are necessary.
default2.5.default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default 
defaultThe safety questidefaulton - Safety in Numbers (SiN):default We think that the experience of London, with a dramatic reduction in cyclist KSIs per journey in the last decade, shows that change has been achieved through SiN. For example, approximately the same number of cyclists is kille
defaultd in collisions with 
defaultlorries
default, with at least a doubling of the amount of cycling in the areas where most deaths occur, and an increase in lorry use. Denying this mechanism denies an important positive step forward, and unnecessarily dissuades people from cy
defaultcling: stopping them from cycling can have a deleterious effect not just on their health but on the safety of other cyclists. However:
default(a)
default&#xa0; 
defaultThis does 
defaultnotdefault mean that SiN 
defaulton its own will
default deliver enough of a  decline in danger
default(b)
default&#xa0; 
defaultSiN is particularly unlikely to be eff
defaultective on roads with very few cyclists and high speed limits, as well as with particularly incompetent drivers or drivers unwilling to drive properly.
default(c)
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThose responsible for danger – whether highway authorities, individual motorists
default,
default motor manufacturers or 
defaultothers – should still be held accountable. Danger should be seen as unacceptable whether or not a collision occurs.
